Gratian loved and revered him as a father and the elaborate treatise on the faith of the Trinity was designed for the instruction of the young prince . 
Ambrose had devoted his life , and his abilities , to the service of the church . 
Wealth was the object of his contempt he had renounced his private patrimony and he sold , without hesitation , the consecrated plate , for the redemption of captives . 
The clergy and people of Milan were attached to their archbishop and he deserved the esteem , without soliciting the favor , or apprehending the displeasure , of his feeble sovereigns . 
Martin , and the Dialogues concerning his miracles contain facts adapted to the grossest barbarism , in a style not unworthy of the Augustan age . 
So natural is the alliance between good taste and good sense , that I am always astonished by this contrast . 
