One hundred and fifty years after the glorious deaths of St . 
Paul , the Vatican and the Ostian road were distinguished by the tombs , or rather by the trophies , of those spiritual heroes . 
The new capital of the Eastern world , unable to produce any ancient and domestic trophies , was enriched by the spoils of dependent provinces . 
About fifty years afterwards , the same banks were honored by the presence of Samuel , the judge and prophet of the people of Israel . 
His ashes , deposited in a golden vase , and covered with a silken veil , were delivered by the bishops into each other's hands . 
