M. Chapter XXIX Division Of Roman Empire Between Sons Of Theodosius . 
Part I. Final Division Of The Roman Empire Between The Sons Of Theodosius . 
Reign Of Arcadius And Honorius Administration Of Rufinus And Stilicho . 
Revolt And Defeat Of Gildo In Africa . 
The memory of his virtues still continued , however , to protect the feeble and inexperienced youth of his two sons . 
Arcadius , who was then about eighteen years of age , was born in Spain , in the humble habitation of a private family . 
The gradual discovery of the weakness of Arcadius and Honorius , and the repeated calamities of their reign , were not sufficient to obliterate the deep and early impressions of loyalty . 
He was raised , by just degrees , to the station of master of the offices . 
This act of violence was represented to the emperor as an insult , which it was incumbent on his dignity to resent . 
was imputed to the perfidious arts of Rufinus . 
The two praefects were accused of rapine and corruption in the administration of the laws and finances . 
He was instantly seized , examined , condemned , and beheaded , in one of the suburbs of Constantinople , with a precipitation which disappointed the clemency of the emperor . 
and perhaps desired , the relief of a speedy death , he was permitted to consume the miserable remnant of his old age in poverty and exile . 
was not diverted , however , by the most criminal pursuits , from the performance of the religious duties , which in that age were considered as the most essential to salvation . 
In the suburb of Chalcedon , surnamed the Oak , he had built a magnificent villa to which he devoutly added a stately church , consecrated to the apostles St . 
Paul , and continually sanctified by the prayers and penance of a regular society of monks . 
