Chapter XXX Revolt Of The Goths . 
The emperor Honorius was distinguished , above his subjects , by the preeminence of fear , as well as of rank . 
The arts of flattery concealed the impending danger , till Alaric approached the palace of Milan . 
The fortresses of the Rhine were abandoned and the safety of Gaul was protected only by the faith of the Germans , and the ancient terror of the Roman name . 
The prudence and vigor of Stilicho were conspicuous on this occasion , which revealed , at the same time , the weakness of the falling empire . 
