M. But the reign of Stilicho drew towards its end and the proud minister might perceive the symptoms of his approaching disgrace . 
The generous boldness of Lampadius had been applauded and the senate , so patiently resigned to a long servitude , rejected with disdain the offer of invidious and imaginary freedom . 
Yet Stilicho might have continued to brave the clamors of the people , and even of the soldiers , if he could have maintained his dominion over the feeble mind of his pupil . 
But the respectful attachment of Honorius was converted into fear , suspicion , and hatred . 
Instead of residing in the palace of Rome , Honorius declared that it was his pleasure to return to the secure fortress of Ravenna . 
His strenuous but ineffectual efforts confirmed the triumph of Olympius and the prudent lawyer withdrew himself from the impending ruin of his patron . 
He came from the coast of the Euxine , and exercised a splendid office . 
His actions justify his character , which Zosimus exposes with visible satisfaction . 
But these praises , which the African saint so unworthily bestows , might proceed as well from ignorance as from adulation . 
Stilicho offered to undertake the journey to Constantinople , that he might divert Honorius from the vain attempt . 
The Eastern empire would not have obeyed , and could not have been conquered . 
Instead of executing a resolution , which might have been justified by success , Stilicho hesitated till he was irrecoverably lost . 
The confederates , impatient of his timorous and doubtful delay , hastily retired , with fear and indignation . 
Olympius , who had assumed the dominion of Honorius , was speedily informed , that his rival had embraced , as a suppliant the altar of the Christian church . 
The base and cruel disposition of the hypocrite was incapable of pity or remorse but he piously affected to elude , rather than to violate , the privilege of the sanctuary . 
Count Heraclian , with a troop of soldiers , appeared , at the dawn of day , before the gates of the church of Ravenna . 
has copiously , though not clearly , related the disgrace and death of Stilicho . 
His family , united by a triple alliance with the family of Theodosius , might envy the condition of the meanest peasant . 
The services of Stilicho are great and manifest his crimes , as they are vaguely stated in the language of flattery and hatred , are obscure at least , and improbable . 
Even the religion of Stilicho was arraigned by the malice of his rival . 
The son of Stilicho , however , was educated in the bosom of Christianity , which his father had uniformly professed , and zealously supported . 
The pride and power of Stilicho constituted his real guilt . 
