Chapter XXXII Emperors Arcadius , Eutropius , Theodosius II . 
Part I. Arcadius Emperor Of The East . 
Administration And Disgrace Of Eutropius . 
The Persian War , And Division Of Armenia . 
The place of Constantinople rivalled , and perhaps excelled , the magnificence of Persia and the eloquent sermons of St . 
Chrysostom celebrate , while they condemn , the pompous luxury of the reign of Arcadius . 
The emperor , says he , wears on his head either a diadem , or a crown of gold , decorated with precious stones of inestimable value . 
These ornaments , and his purple garments , are reserved for his sacred person alone and his robes of silk are embroidered with the figures of golden dragons . 
His throne is of massy gold . 
Whenever he appears in public , he is surrounded by his courtiers , his guards , and his attendants . 
The two mules that drew the chariot of the monarch are perfectly white , and shining all over with gold . 
The successors of Constantine established their perpetual residence in the royal city , which he had erected on the verge of Europe and Asia . 
They were ignorant how much this passive disposition enervates and degrades every faculty of the mind . 
