The council of Eutropius , in Claudian , may be compared to that of Domitian in the fourth Satire of Juvenal . 
The principal members of the former were juvenes protervi lascivique senes one of them had been a cook , a second a woolcomber . 
The language of their original profession exposes their assumed dignity and their trifling conversation about tragedies , dancers , c . 
