The sixth book of Socrates , the eighth of Sozomen , and the fifth of Theodoret , afford curious and authentic materials for the life of John Chrysostom . 
Besides those general historians , I have taken for my guides the four principal biographers of the saint . 
It is inserted among the works of Chrysostom . 
His vivacity and good sense were his own his errors , in the uncultivated state of ecclesiastical antiquity , were almost inevitable . 
who compiles the lives of the saints with incredible patience and religious accuracy . 
He has minutely searched the voluminous works of Chrysostom himself . 
yet the good taste of the former is sometimes vitiated by an excessive love of antiquity and the good sense of the latter is always restrained by prudential considerations . 
When Chrysostom thundered , from the pulpit of St . 
Sophia , against the degeneracy of the Christians , his shafts were spent among the crowd , without wounding , or even marking , the character of any individual . 
The secret resentment of the court encouraged the discontent of the clergy and monks of Constantinople , who were too hastily reformed by the fervent zeal of their archbishop . 
Chrysostom was naturally of a choleric disposition . 
In his visitation through the Asiatic provinces , he deposed thirteen bishops of Lydia and Phrygia and indiscreetly declared that a deep corruption of simony and licentiousness had infected the whole episcopal order . 
If those bishops were innocent , such a rash and unjust condemnation must excite a well grounded discontent . 
The females of Constantinople distinguished themselves by their enmity or their attachment to Chrysostom . 
Olympias , by equal zeal , displayed in a more pious cause , has obtained the title of saint . 
Sozomen , and more especially Socrates , have defined the real character of Chrysostom with a temperate and impartial freedom , very offensive to his blind admirers . 
Those historians lived in the next generation , when party violence was abated , and had conversed with many persons intimately acquainted with the virtues and imperfections of the saint . 
very seriously defends the archbishop . 
The weakness of his stomach required a peculiar diet . 
Business , or study , or devotion , often kept him fasting till sunset . 
He detested the noise and levity of great dinners . 
He saved the expense for the use of the poor . 
He was apprehensive , in a capital like Constantinople , of the envy and reproach of partial invitations . 
that the number of bishops , who might be saved , bore a very small proportion to those who would be damned . 
