The generous mind of Count Boniface was tortured by the exquisite distress of beholding the ruin which he had occasioned , and whose rapid progress he was unable to check . 
After the loss of a battle he retired into Hippo Regius where he was immediately besieged by an enemy , who considered him as the real bulwark of Africa . 
The military labors , and anxious reflections , of Count Boniface , were alleviated by the edifying conversation of his friend St . 
