G. The monastic profession of the ancients was an act of voluntary devotion . 
The inconstant fanatic was threatened with the eternal vengeance of the God whom he deserted but the doors of the monastery were still open for repentance . 
The examples of scandal , and the progress of superstition , suggested the propriety of more forcible restraints . 
After a sufficient trial , the fidelity of the novice was secured by a solemn and perpetual vow and his irrevocable engagement was ratified by the laws of the church and state . 
