Gregory of Tours exhibits a very different picture . 
Perhaps it would not be easy , within the same historical space , to find more vice and less virtue . 
We are continually shocked by the union of savage and corrupt manners . 
the extent and limits of the French monarchy . 
The Franks , or French , are the only people of Europe who can deduce a perpetual succession from the conquerors of the Western empire . 
But their conquest of Gaul was followed by ten centuries of anarchy and ignorance . 
At length the eye of criticism and philosophy was directed to the antiquities of France but even philosophers have been tainted by the contagion of prejudice and passion . 
Yet the sharp conflict has usefully exercised the adverse powers of learning and genius and each antagonist , alternately vanquished and victorious has extirpated some ancient errors , and established some interesting truths . 
has truly and agreeably represented the slow progress of these studies and he observes , that Gregory of Tours was only once printed before the year . 
Germany received with indifference and contempt the codes of Barbaric laws , which were published by Heroldus , Lindenbrogius , c . 
The rudest , or the most servile , condition of human society , is regulated , however , by some fixed and general rules . 
The same care was extended to their vassals and the rude institutions of the Alemanni and Bavarians were diligently compiled and ratified by the supreme authority of the Merovingian kings . 
The Visigoths and Burgundians , whose conquests in Gaul preceded those of the Franks , showed less impatience to attain one of the principal benefits of civilized society . 
Thus , by a singular coincidence , the Germans framed their artless institutions , at a time when the elaborate system of Roman jurisprudence was finally consummated . 
I have derived much instruction from two learned works of Heineccius , the History , and the Elements , of the Germanic law . 
In a judicious preface to the Elements , he considers , and tries to excuse the defects of that barbarous jurisprudence . 
Latin appears to have been the original language of the Salic law . 
