Part V. In a century of perpetual , or at least implacable , war , much courage , and some skill , must have been exerted for the defence of Britain . 
Ambrosius Aurelian was descended from a noble family of Romans his modesty was equal to his valor , and his valor , till the last fatal action , was crowned with splendid success . 
But every British name is effaced by the illustrious name of Arthur , the hereditary prince of the Silures , in South Wales , and the elective king or general of the nation . 
The events of his life are less interesting than the singular revolutions of his fame . 
His trophies were decorated with captive provinces and Imperial titles and his Danish victories avenged the recent injuries of his country . 
Pilgrimage , and the holy wars , introduced into Europe the specious miracles of Arabian magic . 
